    "content_hash": "sha256:be6646bdef5e009ae1008fb0b54f5497f32ede736556baf10cc9dcddd124e593",
    "summary": "The Byzantine Empire (conventionally 330–1453 AD, with roots in the [[event:2030|Founding of Constantinople]] and the [[event:2790|Division Roman Empire]]) was the eastern continuation of the Roman Empire that survived the fall of the Western half in 476 AD by over a thousand years, preserving Roman law, Greek learning, Christian Orthodox theology, and classical civilization through the European Dark Ages and transmitting them to the Renaissance. At its foundation by [[event:2027|Constantine the Great]], Constantinople on the Bosphorus was established as the new Roman capital — 'New Rome' — which proved far more defensible than Rome itself.\n\nThe Byzantine state combined the Roman administrative tradition, Greek language and culture, and Eastern Orthodox Christianity into a distinctive civilization. Justinian I (527–565 AD) briefly reconquered much of the Western Mediterranean and codified Roman law in the Corpus Juris Civilis — the foundation of legal systems across Europe. Byzantine art, with its gold mosaic theology in churches from Ravenna to Constantinople, developed a distinctive visual language that shaped Orthodox Christian art across Eastern Europe, Russia, and the Balkans. The empire weathered Arab conquests (7th–8th centuries), Crusader assaults (1204 sack of Constantinople), and Mongol pressure before finally succumbing to the Ottoman Turks in 1453.\n\nByzantium's legacy is incalculable: it preserved and transmitted classical Greek texts, maintaining continuity with ancient philosophy and science; its legal code shaped the civil law tradition of continental Europe; its Orthodox Christianity spread to Bulgaria, Serbia, Russia, and Romania; and the flight of Byzantine scholars to Italy after 1453 catalyzed the Renaissance. The Byzantine Empire was the longest-lived state in European history.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byzantine_Empire",
